#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml308(orgname)
msgid "CSS Corp- Open Source Services"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml310(title)
msgid "Image management"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml312(para)
msgid ""
"by <link href=\"http://www.csscorp.com/\">CSS Corp Open Source "
"Services</link>"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml315(para)
msgid ""
"There are several pre-built images for OpenStack available from various "
"sources. You can download such images and use them to get familiar with "
"OpenStack. You can refer to <link href=\"http://docs.openstack.org/cactus"
"/openstack-compute/admin/content/starting-"
"images.html\">http://docs.openstack.org/cactus/openstack-"
"compute/admin/content/starting-images.html</link> for details on using such "
"images."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml322(para)
msgid ""
"For any production deployment, you may like to have the ability to bundle "
"custom images, with a custom set of applications or configuration. This "
"chapter will guide you through the process of creating Linux images of "
"Debian and Redhat based distributions from scratch. We have also covered an "
"approach to bundling Windows images."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml328(para)
msgid ""
"There are some minor differences in the way you would bundle a Linux image, "
"based on the distribution. Ubuntu makes it very easy by providing cloud-init"
" package, which can be used to take care of the instance configuration at "
"the time of launch. cloud-init handles importing ssh keys for password-less "
"login, setting hostname etc. The instance acquires the instance specific "
"configuration from Nova-compute by connecting to a meta data interface "
"running on 169.254.169.254."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml337(para)
msgid ""
"While creating the image of a distro that does not have cloud-init or an "
"equivalent package, you may need to take care of importing the keys etc. by "
"running a set of commands at boot time from rc.local."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml341(para)
msgid ""
"The process used for Ubuntu and Fedora is largely the same with a few minor "
"differences, which are explained below."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml345(para)
msgid ""
"In both cases, the documentation below assumes that you have a working KVM "
"installation to use for creating the images. We are using the machine called"
" ‘client1′ as explained in the chapter on “Installation and Configuration” "
"for this purpose."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml351(para)
msgid ""
"The approach explained below will give you disk images that represent a disk"
" without any partitions. Nova-compute can resize such disks ( including "
"resizing the file system) based on the instance type chosen at the time of "
"launching the instance. These images cannot have ‘bootable’ flag and hence "
"it is mandatory to have associated kernel and ramdisk images. These kernel "
"and ramdisk images need to be used by nova-compute at the time of launching "
"the instance."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml360(para)
msgid ""
"However, we have also added a small section towards the end of the chapter "
"about creating bootable images with multiple partitions that can be be used "
"by nova to launch an instance without the need for kernel and ramdisk "
"images. The caveat is that while nova-compute can re-size such disks at the "
"time of launching the instance, the file system size is not altered and "
"hence, for all practical purposes, such disks are not re-sizable."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml369(title)
msgid "Creating a Linux Image – Ubuntu &amp; Fedora"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml372(para)
msgid ""
"The first step would be to create a raw image on Client1. This will "
"represent the main HDD of the virtual machine, so make sure to give it as "
"much space as you will need."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml376(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"kvm-img create -f raw server.img 5G\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml381(title)
msgid "OS Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml382(para)
msgid ""
"Download the iso file of the Linux distribution you want installed in the "
"image. The instructions below are tested on Ubuntu 11.04 Natty Narwhal "
"64-bit server and Fedora 14 64-bit. Most of the instructions refer to "
"Ubuntu. The points of difference between Ubuntu and Fedora are mentioned "
"wherever required."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml389(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"wget http://releases.ubuntu.com/natty/ubuntu-11.04-server-amd64.iso\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml392(para)
msgid ""
"Boot a KVM Instance with the OS installer ISO in the virtual CD-ROM. This "
"will start the installation process. The command below also sets up a VNC "
"display at port 0"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml396(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo kvm -m 256 -cdrom ubuntu-11.04-server-amd64.iso -drive   file=server.img,if=scsi,index=0 -boot d -net nic -net user -nographic  -vnc :0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml399(para)
msgid ""
"Connect to the VM through VNC (use display number :0) and finish the "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml401(para)
msgid "For Example, where 10.10.10.4 is the IP address of client1:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml403(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
" vncviewer 10.10.10.4 :0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml406(para)
msgid ""
"During the installation of Ubuntu, create a single ext4 partition mounted on"
" ‘/’. Do not create a swap partition."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml409(para)
msgid ""
"In the case of Fedora 14, the installation will not progress unless you "
"create a swap partition. Please go ahead and create a swap partition."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml414(para)
msgid ""
"After finishing the installation, relaunch the VM by executing the following"
" command."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml416(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo kvm -m 256 -drive file=server.img,if=scsi,index=0,boot=on -boot c -net nic -net user -nographic -vnc :0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml419(para)
msgid ""
"At this point, you can add all the packages you want to have installed, "
"update the installation, add users and make any configuration changes you "
"want in your image."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml423(para)
msgid "At the minimum, for Ubuntu you may run the following commands"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml425(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo apt-get update\n"
"sudo apt-get upgrade\n"
"sudo apt-get install openssh-server cloud-init\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml430(para)
msgid "For Fedora run the following commands as root"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml432(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"\n"
"yum update\n"
"yum install openssh-server\n"
"chkconfig sshd on\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml438(para)
msgid ""
"Also remove the network persistence rules from /etc/udev/rules.d as their "
"presence will result in the network interface in the instance coming up as "
"an interface other than eth0."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml442(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo rm -rf /etc/udev/rules.d/70-persistent-net.rules\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml445(para)
msgid "Shutdown the Virtual machine and proceed with the next steps."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml449(title)
msgid "Extracting the EXT4 partition"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml450(para)
msgid ""
"The image that needs to be uploaded to OpenStack needs to be an ext4 "
"filesystem image. Here are the steps to create a ext4 filesystem image from "
"the raw image i.e server.img"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml454(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo losetup  -f  server.img\n"
"sudo losetup -a\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml458(para)
#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml470(para)
msgid "You should see an output like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml459(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"/dev/loop0: [0801]:16908388 ($filepath)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml462(para)
msgid ""
"Observe the name of the loop device ( /dev/loop0 in our setup) when "
"$filepath is the path to the mounted .raw file."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml465(para)
msgid "Now we need to find out the starting sector of the partition. Run:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml467(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo fdisk -cul /dev/loop0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml472(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"Disk /dev/loop0: 5368 MB, 5368709120 bytes\n"
"149 heads, 8 sectors/track, 8796 cylinders, total 10485760 sectors\n"
"Units = sectors of 1 * 512 = 512 bytes\n"
"Sector size (logical/physical): 512 bytes / 512 bytes\n"
"I/O size (minimum/optimal): 512 bytes / 512 bytes\n"
"Disk identifier: 0x00072bd4\n"
"Device Boot      Start         End      Blocks   Id  System\n"
"/dev/loop0p1   *        2048    10483711     5240832   83  Linux\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml482(para)
msgid ""
"Make a note of the starting sector of the /dev/loop0p1 partition i.e the "
"partition whose ID is 83. This number should be multiplied by 512 to obtain "
"the correct value. In this case: 2048 x 512 = 1048576"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml487(para)
msgid "Unmount the loop0 device:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml488(screen)
#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml515(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo losetup -d /dev/loop0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml491(para)
msgid ""
"Now mount only the partition(/dev/loop0p1) of server.img which we had "
"previously noted down, by adding the -o parameter with value previously "
"calculated value"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml495(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo losetup -f -o 1048576 server.img\n"
"sudo losetup -a\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml499(para)
msgid "You’ll see a message like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml500(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"/dev/loop0: [0801]:16908388 ($filepath) offset 1048576\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml503(para)
msgid ""
"Make a note of the mount point of our device(/dev/loop0 in our setup) when "
"$filepath is the path to the mounted .raw file."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml506(para)
msgid "Copy the entire partition to a new .raw file"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml508(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo dd if=/dev/loop0 of=serverfinal.img\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml511(para)
msgid "Now we have our ext4 filesystem image i.e serverfinal.img"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml514(para)
msgid "Unmount the loop0 device"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml520(title)
msgid "Tweaking /etc/fstab"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml521(para)
msgid ""
"You will need to tweak /etc/fstab to make it suitable for a cloud instance. "
"Nova-compute may resize the disk at the time of launch of instances based on"
" the instance type chosen. This can make the UUID of the disk invalid. Hence"
" we have to use File system label as the identifier for the partition "
"instead of the UUID."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml528(para)
msgid "Loop mount the serverfinal.img, by running"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml530(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo mount -o loop serverfinal.img /mnt\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml533(para)
msgid ""
"Edit /mnt/etc/fstab and modify the line for mounting root partition(which "
"may look like the following)"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml540(para)
msgid "to"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml547(title)
msgid "Fetching Metadata in Fedora"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml548(para)
msgid ""
"Since, Fedora does not ship with cloud-init or an equivalent, you will need "
"to take a few steps to have the instance fetch the meta data like ssh keys "
"etc."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml552(para)
msgid ""
"Edit the /etc/rc.local file and add the following lines before the line "
"“touch /var/lock/subsys/local”"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml572(title)
msgid "Kernel and Initrd for OpenStack"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml574(para)
msgid ""
"Copy the kernel and the initrd image from /mnt/boot to user home directory. "
"These will be used later for creating and uploading a complete virtual image"
" to OpenStack."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml578(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo cp /mnt/boot/vmlinuz-2.6.38-7-server /home/localadmin\n"
"sudo cp /mnt/boot/initrd.img-2.6.38-7-server /home/localadmin\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml582(para)
msgid "Unmount the Loop partition"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml583(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo umount  /mnt\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml586(para)
msgid "Change the filesystem label of serverfinal.img to ‘uec-rootfs’"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml588(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo tune2fs -L uec-rootfs serverfinal.img\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml591(para)
msgid ""
"Now, we have all the components of the image ready to be uploaded to "
"OpenStack imaging server."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml595(title)
msgid "Registering with OpenStack"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml596(para)
msgid ""
"The last step would be to upload the images to Openstack Imaging Server "
"glance. The files that need to be uploaded for the above sample setup of "
"Ubuntu are: vmlinuz-2.6.38-7-server, initrd.img-2.6.38-7-server, "
"serverfinal.img"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml601(para)
msgid "Run the following command"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml602(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"uec-publish-image -t image --kernel-file vmlinuz-2.6.38-7-server --ramdisk-file initrd.img-2.6.38-7-server amd64 serverfinal.img bucket1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml605(para)
msgid ""
"For Fedora, the process will be similar. Make sure that you use the right "
"kernel and initrd files extracted above."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml608(para)
msgid ""
"The uec-publish-image command returns the prompt back immediately. However, "
"the upload process takes some time and the images will be usable only after "
"the process is complete. You can keep checking the status using the command "
"<command>nova image-list</command> as mentioned below."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml616(title)
msgid "Bootable Images"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml617(para)
msgid ""
"You can register bootable disk images without associating kernel and ramdisk"
" images. When you do not want the flexibility of using the same disk image "
"with different kernel/ramdisk images, you can go for bootable disk images. "
"This greatly simplifies the process of bundling and registering the images. "
"However, the caveats mentioned in the introduction to this chapter apply. "
"Please note that the instructions below use server.img and you can skip all "
"the cumbersome steps related to extracting the single ext4 partition."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/common/ch_image_mgmt.xml628(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"glance add name=\"My Server\" is_public=true container_format=ovf disk_format=raw &lt; server.img\n"
msgstr ""

